Vertiv NetSure 2100 — -48 V DC Power System, controller and rectifier module manual (excerpt). Vendor: Vertiv. Deployed as the DC plant at macro cell sites; Flatpack2-class rectifier shelves, NCU controller, N+1 redundancy.

## Plant architecture and N+1 redundancy

A NetSure 2100 -48 V DC plant supplies the site load from a shelf of rectifier modules operating in parallel onto a common -48 V bus, backed by VRLA battery strings. The plant is engineered N+1: with the site at its design load, one rectifier module can be lost without the bus leaving float, because the remaining modules redistribute the current. A single failed module therefore degrades redundancy, not service — the bus stays at float and the batteries are not called upon while N modules still carry the load. If lost rectifier capacity exceeds the N+1 margin, however, the bus falls, a genuine DC undervoltage develops, and the batteries begin to discharge. This is why a lone rectifier-lost alarm on a healthy plant is non-urgent, but a rectifier fault together with a falling bus is a real undervoltage that must be acted on.

## Rectifier Lost and Rectifier Comms Fail alarm signatures

"Rectifier Lost" is raised when the controller stops seeing a module that was previously present: the module status contact opens, its output current falls to zero and its front LED goes dark. On the SNMP feed this maps to a major rectifier trap (alarmMajorRectifier). "Rectifier Comms Fail" is a lesser alarm where the module still delivers current but has dropped off the controller bus. The genuine-undervoltage signature is the coherent one: a rectifier module fault (module_status fail on the affected module, e.g. rectifier-2) occurring together with a bus that sags below the undervoltage limit and battery-discharge current. When these telemetry signals corroborate one another they confirm a real DC undervoltage caused by lost rectifier capacity — a genuine physical plant fault — and the remedy is to restore capacity by replacing the failed module (part APR48-3G). A dark module LED with a genuinely low measured bus is a real module failure, not a monitoring artifact.

## Bus voltage, float and behaviour on module loss

Normal float for a 24-cell VRLA plant is about -54.4 V (2.27 V/cell). On loss of a single module with N+1 redundancy intact the bus remains at float. If lost capacity exceeds redundancy the bus genuinely falls, the controller reports a real DC undervoltage, and the batteries discharge — an internally consistent low-voltage signature (low bus + rectifier module fault + discharge current) that points to a real plant fault. A bus measured low at the bar (for example around -44.8 V) alongside a rectifier module fault confirms a genuine undervoltage; replace the failed module (APR48-3G) to restore capacity. After replacement, confirm the bus returns to float near -54.4 V before closing the job.

## Rectifier module hot-swap replacement procedure

NetSure rectifier modules are hot-swappable and replaced without interrupting the DC output. Precondition: verify the plant is carrying the load on N-1 / N+1 redundancy so extraction will not drop the bus. Sequence: identify the failed module by dark LED and zero output; release the module latch and extract it from the shelf; insert the replacement module of the same type (Eaton/Vertiv 48 V / 2000 W class, part APR48-3G) and confirm it powers up, joins the controller, and shares load; verify the bus is at float near -54.4 V and the Rectifier Lost alarm clears. Because the swap is hot and the plant holds on redundancy, a single module replacement can be booked into the next maintenance window when N+1 redundancy is holding and the bus is confirmed healthy.

## Undervoltage indication and the controller sense path

A DC undervoltage indication normally reflects a real low bus. The controller senses the bus and reports it, and by default a low report is a real sag — most so when it co-occurs with a rectifier module fault and battery discharge, a coherent signature of a genuine plant undervoltage. The controller's sensing should be questioned only in the one specific case where an independent field measurement taken at the distribution bar contradicts the reported value — the bus measured at normal float while the controller still reports undervoltage. Absent that contradicting measurement, treat the undervoltage as real and act on the rectifier fault.
